    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Defining Science</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>George E Lamb letter on Nov 15 article about Kansas School Board decision to adopt new standards that include teaching of intelligent design theory in science classes holds that science should not be politicized</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Philosophers Notwithstanding, Kansas School Board Redefines Science'' (Nov. 15): The extremists on the political left and their literary and academic allies took objectivity out of lay discussions of science some time ago. Whether the subject was global warming, global winter, bee dung in the jungle, petroleum reserves or something else, actual findings were subjected to a political test before being accepted by the left.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Philosophers Notwithstanding, Kansas School Board Redefines Science'' (Nov. 15): The extremists on the political left and their literary and academic allies took objectivity out of lay discussions of science some time ago. Whether the subject was global warming, global winter, bee dung in the jungle, petroleum reserves or something else, actual findings were subjected to a political test before being accepted by the left.</p>
        <p>Now that they have succeeded in convincing themselves that everything is subjective and therefore political, they are reaping the whirlwind caused by their counterpart know-nothings on the right. A pox on both groups.</p>
        <p>Scientific inquiry requires considerable humility and the willingness to admit that your latest theory may be untenable in light of later findings. Humility is in short supply among brilliant scientists and is unknown among those who think the Almighty speaks directly to them.</p>
        <p>George E. Lamb  Seattle</p>
      </block>
